title: Memory pattern enhancements - Part 2
body:
- Introduces partial memory pattern generation in scenarios where ahead of model execution there are _unknown symbolic shapes_ that _today_ prevent _any_ static planning from taking place, this disables tensor contiguous allocation feature that is used by ncclAllReduce kernel.

-  Removes memory blocks from static allocation at runtime if their size does not match the actual size of the tensor and then try to reallocate them from the static buffer with the correct size.

- Enhances dynamic allocations by first searching for free memory blocks in static buffer before going to BFCArena.

- Fixes a long standing bug in [CalculateMemoryPatternsKey](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/00412a76e91d85d0ccba57ac8198bb4b73beab2d/onnxruntime/core/framework/session_state.cc#L295) that uses a suboptimal hashing algorithm which results in collision in below scenarios:

  `Graph` input shapes 1: 17,57,17,17,57,17,57,1,1,20,23,20,20,32,20,32,1,1,9,56,9,9,73,9,73,1,1,1

  > both yielded the same key (23), even though they are very different input shapes and there are bunch of other examples.

- Verified this change with one of the models that had several unknown symbolic shapes is no longer getting out of memory exception.

title: Using a map of of ops to stages as input of partition function.
body:
### Description

This PR adds capability to explicitly define partition using a mapping of graph nodes to pipeline stages. See the PipelinePartition.DropoutGraph2stages for an example. 

In particular, we changed the “ApplyPipelinePartitionToMainGraph” code to use this mapping, we added a function “GetDeviceAssignmentMap” to convert the existing “cut_info” formulation to the new formulation (the partition definitions from before this PR should still work), and included new unit tests to compare the outputs of both partitions. 

As we want to avoid keeping two different partition functions, we moved the cut-based partition code to a partition_utils testing file.

### Motivation

The motivation for this work comes from the inability to partition certain graphs using the current partition API and algorithm. 
For example, we were not able to achieve the partitioning of the following graph:
```
graph(in):
      a = foo(in)     # Want to place on stage 0
      b = bar(a)    # Want to place on stage 1
      c = baz(b)   # Want to place on stage 2
      d = add(b, c)  # Want to place on stage 1
      e = mul(a, d)  # Want to place on stage 0
      e
```

We may want to achieve such partition _before_ AD to avoid copying large weights to a different device, for example. Note that this graph has similar shape to a training graph with pipeline parallelism and that we can easily extend the new partition algorithm to run _after_ AD, allowing for more flexible pipelines. This is the first PR towards more general pipeline parallelism.

title: save data to and load data from an hdf5 file for checkpointing
body:
**Description**: Implementation of internal utility functions for saving to and loading from hdf5 file. These functions are useful for ```ORTTrainer``` checkpointing functionality.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
These changes are required to save and load an ```ORTTrainer``` checkpoint to and from an hdf5 file. 
  - More details on why hdf5 file format is required for ```ORTTrainer``` checkpointing:

    The main reason for a special file format is related to distributed training. In a distributed training scenario, each worker (or process) would write its own states to an output file. It is important to map each checkpoint file to its original rank along with the distributed environment training configuration, such as world size and type of distributed training. The existing checkpoint design embeds such information on filenames (e.g. common prefix along with world_rank, workd_size and other such parameters (encoded as strings) on the file name). This is necessary in order to correctly identify the rank of the file being loaded so it can be loaded into the corresponding trainer or to aggregate all checkpoints in proper order. But naming the files as such has certain drawbacks:
    - File names cannot be changed, affecting future extensions and BC concerns.
    - All checkpoint files need to reside in the same folder.
    - Since there is a default prefix name is hardcoded in the API, the file can be easily mistakenly overwritten.
    - Rank, world size and other ZeRO information is embedded in the file name.

    The proposal is to embed relevant metadata inside the file, which could have any friendly name as per the users liking. While loading, each file is partially read to build a map. Using pickle is avoided because it would require loading the entire checkpoint file (which could be huge) and discarding it in case it does not align with the one we are looking for. Here is where hdf5 comes into play. Hdf5 file format allows us to read only a part of the file (relevant metadata). This should enable us to build the rank to file name map fast and easily.

title: Update build docker image cache cleanup
body:
**Description**
The current image cache cleanup is not removing many images. Upon examining the cache container registry logs, it appears there are some infrequent pulls of old images which may be made by something other than CI builds (perhaps some automated scan of the registry).
This change adds a minimum access count for images in the cache so that infrequently but periodically accessed images can be removed. The idea is that images used by CI builds that are worth caching will have a higher volume of accesses.

**Motivation and Context**
Reduce number of cached images.
